    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-09-24T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-09-24T15:00:00-05:00" n="475"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d475">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">882.7962/118: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in Liberia</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hibbard</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-09-24T16:00:00-04:00"
                            >September 24, 1942—4 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>234. Your 297, September 16. McBride is authorized to discuss all pending matters
                    with President Barclay. Question 5 will be taken up with the Board of Economic
                    Warfare. Question 3 is under discussion with Walker.<note n="36"
                        xml:id="d475fn36">Walter F. Walker, Liberian Consul General, New
                        York.</note>
                </p>
                <p>The Department feels that it would be desirable for McBride to proceed to Accra,
                    if he is prepared to do so and if the opportunity offers, to investigate the
                    point raised in question 7, which travel in his discretion is authorized.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
